<div type="definition">
<p>MOVING WATER RESEMBLING MOUNTAIN RIDGE.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The current general word for water in wave-movement is pō 波.</p>
<p>2. Tāo 濤 is a late word referring to large waves.</p>
<p>3. Lián 漣 and lún 淪 are rare words referring to small ripples in water.</p>
<p>4. Cháo 潮 refers to a flood of considerable dimensions without necessarily connoting high waves.</p>
<p>NB: Làng 浪 is a post-Han general term for waves, and focusses specifically to the crest of waves. In pre-Buddhist times the word means "to flow along".</p>
        </div>
